description.en: The Metric model consists of a taxonomy of quantities, quantity kinds and key metrics e.g. KPI (Key Performance Indicator) or KRI (Key Risk Indicator) that are used for quantification, measurement and sensing in engineering domain. More Specifically, it complements further ontologies like QUDT or SSN/SOSA with very specific metrics for e.g. HVAC (Heating Ventilation and Air Conditioning), building automation, building design, energy management, etc. It contrasts to rather more abstract quantities from other vocabularies.

bibliographicCitation.value: Pruvost. H. (2023): The Metric Model - Quantities and Key Indicators for the Architecture, Engineering, Construction, and Facility Management domain. https://w3id.org/mm.

A metric without context i.e. related to no entity like a product or process it can applies to, and without requirements. This is simply the definition of a physical or an abstract measure. Example: energy consumption, number of items, duration...)

comment.undefined: A metric that refers to a design constraints or objective, and that has one or more requirements.

The EER is the ratio of the cooling capacity (in British thermal units (Btu) per hour) to the power input (in watts). 
The higher the EER rating, the more efficient the air conditioner.
A metric that reflects a decision trade-off between several competing objectives, constraints or risks.

The SEER rating of a unit is the cooling output during a typical cooling-season divided by the total electric energy input during the same period. 
The higher the unit's SEER rating the more energy efficient it is.
A metric that refers to the behavior of heating, ventilation and air conditioning systems.
A metric that refers to one or several risks, and that has one or more requirements.
A concrete metric that has a context, namely a product or a process it applies to.
